               <p>HENRY MANN. I am in partnership with 
               <persName id="t18280221-301-victim1676" type="victimName">
                  Alexander 
                  Maloney
               <interp inst="t18280221-301-victim1676" type="surname" value="Maloney"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-301-victim1676" type="given" value="Alexander"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-301-victim1676" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . The prisoner was in my brother's service, and often brought bottles to our premises.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-301-person1677">
                  ROBERT 
                  BENCE
               <interp inst="t18280221-301-person1677" type="surname" value="BENCE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-301-person1677" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-301-person1677" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am cellarman to the prosecutors. On the 11th of January, about five o'clock in the evening, the prisoner brought some bottles to their cellar in Mincing-lane; I heard bottles rattle, looked round, and saw him putting one into his pocket; I asked what he was doing - he said he had picked it up in the street; I desired him to produce it, which he did; I then told him to unbutton himself, and saw one bottle sticking out of his breeches pocket; there was wine in each of them - I gave him in charge.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-301-person1678">
                  JAMES 
                  HALL
               <interp inst="t18280221-301-person1678" type="surname" value="HALL"></interp>
